{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17637252","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17637252"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:40:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:40:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17645"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17645","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17645"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10359"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71765"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10359","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10359"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17645"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57254"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"7741"},{"type":"tags","id":"7743"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24223"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24228"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71765","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71765"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA researcher wants to study student satisfaction with university facilities across different year levels. The university has 5000 students with the following distribution:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EFirst year: 2000 students\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ESecond year: 1500 students\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThird year: 1000 students\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EFourth year: 500 students\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe researcher plans to survey 500 students in total.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the number of students that should be sampled from each year level using proportional stratified sampling?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["125 students from each year level","200 first year, 150 second year, 100 third year, 50 fourth year","250 first year, 125 second year, 75 third year, 50 fourth year","400 first year, 50 second year, 25 third year, 25 fourth year","300 first year, 100 second year, 50 third year, 50 fourth year"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn proportional stratified sampling, the number of subjects selected from each stratum should be proportional to the size of that stratum in the population. With a total sample size of 500 from a population of 5000 (10% sampling fraction), the correct distribution would be:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E200 first year\u003C/strong\u003E (10% of 2000)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E150 second year\u003C/strong\u003E (10% of 1500)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E100 third year\u003C/strong\u003E (10% of 1000)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E50 fourth year\u003C/strong\u003E (10% of 500)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EProportional stratified sampling ensures that each year level is represented in proportion to its size in the population, providing more precise estimates than simple random sampling.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Stratified sampling divides a population into subgroups (strata) before random sampling within each stratum.","Stratified sampling ensures proportional representation of important subgroups in the final sample.","Stratified sampling is more precise than simple random sampling when studying heterogeneous populations."],"references":["Sullivan LM. Essentials of biostatistics in public health. 3rd ed. Burlington (MA): Jones \u0026 Bartlett Learning; 2018.","Dawson B, Trapp RG. Basic \u0026 clinical biostatistics. 4th ed. New York: McGraw-Hill; 2004."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57254"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17645"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57254","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57254"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-20T15:28:02+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-20T15:29:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10359"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71765"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4948","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4948"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udcca","name":"Biostatistics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":nu